rdf:Description.NS0:background: A land of vast distances and rich natural resources, Canada became a self-governing dominion in 1867 while retaining ties to the British crown. Economically and technologically the nation has developed in parallel with the US, its neighbor to the south across an unfortified border. Its paramount political problem continues to be the relationship of the province of Quebec, with its French-speaking residents and unique culture, to the remainder of the country.
rdf:Description.NS0:location: Northern North America, bordering the North Atlantic Ocean and North Pacific Ocean, north of the conterminous US
rdf:Description.NS0:climate: varies from temperate in south to subarctic and arctic in north
rdf:Description.NS0:terrain: mostly plains with mountains in west and lowlands in southeast
rdf:Description.NS0:naturalHazard: continuous permafrost in north is a serious obstacle to development
cyclonic storms form east of the Rocky Mountains, a result of the mixing of air masses from the Arctic, Pacific, and North American interior, and produce most of the country's rain and snow
rdf:Description.NS0:environmentalIssue: air pollution and resulting acid rain severely affecting lakes and damaging forests
metal smelting, coal-burning utilities, and vehicle emissions impacting on agricultural and forest productivity
ocean waters becoming contaminated due to agricultural, industrial, mining, and forestry activities
rdf:Description.NS0:literacyDefinition: age 15 and over can read and write
rdf:Description.NS0:constitution: 17 April 1982 (Constitution Act); originally, the machinery of the government was set up in the British North America Act of 1867; charter of rights and unwritten customs
rdf:Description.NS0:legalSystem: based on English common law, except in Quebec, where civil law system based on French law prevails; accepts compulsory ICJ jurisdiction, with reservations
rdf:Description.NS0:flagDescription: three vertical bands of red (hoist side), white (double width, square), and red with a red maple leaf centered in the white band
rdf:Description.NS0:economyOverview: As an affluent, high-tech industrial society, Canada today closely resembles the US in its market-oriented economic system, pattern of production, and high living standards. Since World War II, the impressive growth of the manufacturing, mining, and service sectors has transformed the nation from a largely rural economy into one primarily industrial and urban. Real rates of growth have averaged nearly 3.0%20 since 1993. Unemployment is falling and government budget surpluses are being partially devoted to reducing the large public sector debt. The 1989 US-Canada Free Trade Agreement (FTA) and 1994 North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) (which included Mexico) have touched off a dramatic increase in trade and economic integration with the US. With its great natural resources, skilled labor force, and modern capital plant Canada enjoys solid economic prospects. Two shadows loom, the first being the continuing constitutional impasse between English- and French-speaking areas, which has been raising the possibility of a split in the federation. Another long-term concern is the flow south to the US of professional persons lured by higher pay, lower taxes, and the immense high-tech infrastructure.
rdf:Description.NS0:telephoneSystemGeneralAssessment: excellent service provided by modern technology
rdf:Description.NS0:telephoneSystemDomestic: domestic satellite system with about 300 earth stations
rdf:Description.NS0:telephoneSystemInternational: 5 coaxial submarine cables; satellite earth stations - 5 Intelsat (4 Atlantic Ocean and 1 Pacific Ocean) and 2 Intersputnik (Atlantic Ocean region)
rdf:Description.NS0:internationalDispute: maritime boundary disputes with the US
rdf:Description.NS0:illicitDrugs: illicit producer of cannabis for the domestic drug market
use of hydroponics technology permits growers to plant large quantities of high-quality marijuana indoors
transit point for heroin and cocaine entering the US market
